<doc id="8887" wikidata="Q1778193" url="?curid=8887" title="Direct product">
<text>In mathematics, a direct product of objects already known can often be defined by giving a new one. That induces a structure on the Cartesian product of the underlying sets from that of the contributing objects. More abstractly, the product in category theory is mentioned, which formalizes those notions.

Examples are the product of sets, groups (described below), rings, and other algebraic structures. The product of topological spaces is another instance.

There is also the direct sum, which in some areas used interchangeably but in others is a different concept.

== Examples ==
* If formula_1 is thought of as the set of real numbers without further structure, the direct product formula_2 is just the Cartesian product formula_3
* If formula_1 is thought of as the group of real numbers under addition, the direct product formula_5 still has formula_6 as its underlying set. The difference between this and the preceding examples is that formula_2 is now a group and so how to add their elements must also be stated. That is done by defining formula_8
* If formula_1 is thought of as the ring of real numbers, the direct product formula_5 again has formula_6 as its underlying set. The ring structure consists of addition defined by formula_12 and multiplication defined by formula_13
* Although the ring formula_1 is a field, formula_2 is not because the nonzero element formula_16 does not have a multiplicative inverse.

In a similar manner, the direct product of finitely many algebraic structures can be talked about; for example, formula_17 That relies on the direct product being associative up to isomorphism. That is, formula_18 for any algebraic structures formula_19 formula_20 and formula_21 of the same kind. The direct product is also commutative up to isomorphism; that is, formula_22 for any algebraic structures formula_23 and formula_24 of the same kind. Even the direct product of infinitely many algebraic structures can be talked about; for example, the direct product of countably many copies of formula_25 is written as formula_26

== Direct product of groups ==

In group theory, define the direct product of two groups formula_27 and formula_28 can be denoted by formula_29 For abelian groups that are written additively, it may also be called the direct sum of two groups, denoted by formula_30

It is defined as follows:
* the set of the elements of the new group is the &quot;Cartesian product&quot; of the sets of elements of formula_31 that is formula_32
* on tse elements put an operation, defined element-wise: formula_33
Note that formula_27 may be the same as formula_35

The construction gives a new group, which has a normal subgroup that is isomorphic to formula_36 (given by the elements of the form formula_37) and one that is isomorphic to formula_38 (comprising the elements formula_39).

The reverse also holds in the recognition theorem. If a group formula_40 contains two normal subgroups formula_31 such that formula_42 and the intersection of formula_43 contains only the identity, formula_40 is isomorphic to formula_29 A relaxation of those conditions by requiring only one subgroup to be normal gives the semidirect product.

For example, formula_43 are taken as two copies of the unique (up to isomorphisms) group of order 2, formula_47 say formula_48 Then, formula_49 with the operation element by element. For instance, formula_50 andformula_51

With a direct product, some natural group homomorphisms are obtained for free: the projection maps defined by
formula_52
are called the coordinate functions.

Also, every homomorphism formula_53 to the direct product is totally determined by its component functions formula_54

For any group formula_27 and any integer formula_56 repeated application of the direct product gives the group of all formula_57-tuples formula_58 (for formula_59 that is the trivial group); for example, formula_60 and formula_61

== Direct product of modules ==
The direct product for modules (not to be confused with the tensor product) is very similar to the one that is defined for groups above by using the Cartesian product with the operation of addition being componentwise, and the scalar multiplication just distributing over all the components. Starting from formula_1, Euclidean space formula_63 is gotten, the prototypical example of a real formula_57-dimensional vector space. The direct product of formula_65 and formula_63 is formula_67

A direct product for a finite index formula_68 is canonically isomorphic to the direct sum formula_69 The direct sum and the direct product are not isomorphic for infinite indices for which the elements of a direct sum are zero for all but for a finite number of entries. They are dual in the sense of category theory: the direct sum is the coproduct, and the direct product is the product.

For example, for formula_70 and formula_71 the infinite direct product and direct sum of the real numbers. Only sequences with a finite number of non-zero elements are in formula_72 For example, formula_73 is in formula_74 but formula_75 is not. Both sequences are in the direct product formula_76 in fact, formula_74 is a proper subset of formula_78 (that is, formula_79).

== Topological space direct product ==
The direct product for a collection of topological spaces formula_80 for formula_81 in formula_82 some index set, once again makes use of the Cartesian product
formula_83

Defining the topology is a little tricky. For finitely many factors, it is the obvious and natural thing to do: simply take as a basis of open sets to be the collection of all Cartesian products of open subsets from each factor:
formula_84

That topology is called the product topology. For example, by directly defining the product topology on formula_85 by the open sets of formula_1 (disjoint unions of open intervals), the basis for that topology would consist of all disjoint unions of open rectangles in the plane (as it turns out, it coincides with the usual metric topology).

The product topology for infinite products has a twist, which has to do with being able to make all the projection maps continuous and to make all functions into the product continuous if and only if all its component functions are continuous (that is, to satisfy the categorical definition of product: the morphisms here are continuous functions). The basis of open sets is taken to be the collection of all Cartesian products of open subsets from each factor, as before, with the proviso that all but finitely many of the open subsets are the entire factor:
formula_87

The more natural-sounding topology would be, in this case, to take products of infinitely many open subsets as before, which yields a somewhat interesting topology, the box topology. However, it is not too difficult to find an example of bunch of continuous component functions whose product function is not continuous (see the separate entry box topology for an example and more). The problem that makes the twist necessary is ultimately rooted in the fact that the intersection of open sets is guaranteed to be open only for finitely many sets in the definition of topology.

Products (with the product topology) are nice with respect to preserving properties of their factors; for example, the product of Hausdorff spaces is Hausdorff, the product of connected spaces is connected, and the product of compact spaces is compact. That last one, called Tychonoff&#x27;s theorem, is yet another equivalence to the axiom of choice.

For more properties and equivalent formulations, see product topology.

